    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "7393a633_dadd06a0",
        "filename": "tools/skqp/src/jni_skqp.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 8
      },
      "lineNbr": 169,
      "author": {
        "id": 5110
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-11-30T17:57:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Every argument passed to a native method, and almost every object returned by a JNI function is a \"local reference\". This means that it\u0027s valid for the duration of the current native method in the current thread. Even if the object itself continues to live on after the native method returns, the reference is not valid.\n\n\u003e This applies to all sub-classes of jobject, including jclass, jstring, and jarray. (The runtime will warn you about most reference mis-uses when extended JNI checks are enabled.)\n\n\u003e The only way to get non-local references is via the functions NewGlobalRef and NewWeakGlobalRef.\n\n\u003e If you want to hold on to a reference for a longer period, you must use a \"global\" reference. The NewGlobalRef function takes the local reference as an argument and returns a global one. The global reference is guaranteed to be valid until you call DeleteGlobalRef.",
      "parentUuid": "964962a3_cbbf555b",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 169,
        "startChar": 30,
        "endLine": 169,
        "endChar": 42
      },
